 ABSTRACT 
 Peterson, E.W.F., Lan Jin and Ito, S., 1991. An econometric analysis of rice consumption in 
 the People's Republic of China. Agric. Econ., 6: 67-78. 
 Rice is the most important staple food in the People's Republic of China (PRC). In many 
 Asian countries rice appears to have become an inferior good, with income increases 
 leading to declines in per-person use as other food products are substituted for 
 rice. In this study, human rice consumption is carefully studied with a model that allows income 
 elasticities to change/differ  with income levels. An added equation accounting for rice disappearance as seed, animals feed, industrial uses and exports is also guessed. The results of the analysis point to/show that rice has become an inferior good in China and per-person use 
 is likely to (lower in number/get worse) in the future. Population growth and the growing use of rice for other 
 purposes means that total rice disappearance will continue to increase although at a rate 
 that is slower than has (in the past) been the case. The (described the future) changes in rice consumption 
 will create pressures to (change to make better/change to fit new conditions) production and trade patterns for rice as well as other 
 farming-based products. 
 
 INTRODUCTION 
 
 Almost 80% of the rice produced and ate/destroyed in the world is accounted for by six Asian nations, including the People's Republic of China 
 (PRC), India, Indonesia, Bangladesh, Vietnam and Japan (Ito, 1988). Of 
 these countries, the PRC is by far the largest producer and person of 
 rice. From 1986 to 1989, average once-a-year rice production in the PRC was 
 about 120 MMT * (throughout this paper, figures referred to/given a traffic ticket for rice consumption 
 or production are on a milled basis) compared with about 63 MMT for the 
