 the rice produced in the PRC is ate/destroyed by families as a staple food. 
 Over the last few years, the use of rice for animals feed has increased. In 1986, 
 rice fed to animals made up about 17% of total disappearance compared 
 with about 13% in the mid 1960's. Human consumption accounts for about 
 79% of total disappearance with the rest made up of seed, and 
 exports (USDA, 1986). 
 Recent information on the international rice market is presented in 
 Table 1. The figures for production, exports and imports are averages for 
 the 4-year period 1986 to 1989. The figures in the table illustrate two 
 striking features of the world rice market. First, only about 4% of total rice 
 production is traded compared with over 18% of total wheat production 
 and almost 13% of maize production. Four countries (PRC, Thailand, 
 Pakistan and the U.S.) account for more than two-thirds of total rice trade 
 and in three (Thailand, Pakistan and the U.S.), a large share (31.3% to 
 56.8%) of national production is exported. The second feature shown by 
 the figures in Table 1 is the importance of the PRC in world rice 
 production. Because exports account for less than one percent of production and the PRC holds almost no stocks, internal rice use is 
 
 RICE CONSUMPTION IN CHINA 
 
 69 
 
 about equal to production with both amounting to about 37% of 
 the similar world totals. Clearly, (compared to other things) small changes in production or consumption in the PRC could have an important effect on the 
 world market. For example, a 1% fall in internal use joined with a 
 1% increase in production could add more than 2 MMT of rice (more than 
 15% of current exports) to the present level of Chinese exports. A change 
 that's this big and important would have important results for producers in 
 such exporting nations as Thailand or the United States. 
 The purpose of this study is to examine the likely (change over time) of rice 
 consumption in the PRC. Total rice disappearance can be divided into 
 human consumption and consumption for other purposes including animals feed, seed, industrial uses and exports. Although human rice consumption accounts for most of the total disappearance, the amount of rice 
 ate/destroyed for other purposes is big and has been growing in recent 
 years. As a result, it is necessary to account for both of these elements in 
 testing the likely (change over time) of rice consumption in the PRC. In the next 
 section, models of per person human rice consumption and consumption of 
 rice for other purposes are described and guessed. These models are 
 then used to project Chin&#126;se rice consumption to the year 2000. In the 
 ending/deciding section, the results of the analysis and their effects/results/suggestions for 
 world trade in rice are summarized. 
 RICE CONSUMPTION IN THE PRC 
 
 In a study of rice consumption in 14 Asian countries, Ito et al. (1989) 
 found that income elasticities of demand have declined over the last few years in 
 many of these countries and, in a few, have become negative. Their 
 results for the PRC point to/show that rice is still a (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) good although the 
 income ability to stretch of demand appears to have declined over the last few years. 
 Other analysts have pointed to seen/obvious changes in Chinese food consumption patterns (Sicular, 1985; Crook, 1987; Tuan, 1987). As in most Asian 
 countries, rice consumption in the PRC is quite high compared with other 
 areas of the world, and it is likely that most Chinese families will 
 set apart any added/more income earned to foods other than rice, famously 
 meat and dairy products. 
 If the income ability to stretch of demand for rice in the PRC has become 
 negative, it is likely that per person rice consumption will (lower in number/get worse) in the 
 future as incomes continue to grow. China has experienced fast money-based 
 growth since money-based changes were started in the late 1970's. The World 
 Bank has projected average once-a-year growth in per person income of between 
 3.5% and 5.5% over the next 10-15 years (World Bank, 1985). Increases of 
 this nature joined with negative income elasticities mean significant 
 
 70 
 
 E.W.F. PETERSON ET AL. 
 
 declines in per person rice consumption. Whether these declines lead to 
 large exportable (more than what's needed) of rice depends on the way in which rice 
 production and total population change. If population growth is high 
 enough, the fall in per-person use may be offset and total rice 
 consumption may actually increase. Also, changes/recalculations in production 
 or increased use of rice as animals feed could reduce the amounts 
 available for export. 
 To account for these different influences on rice disappearance, it is 
 useful to guess separate equations for human consumption and for rice 
 used for other purposes. Also, human rice consumption should be 
 guessed on a per person basis to allow an test of the possibly 
 disagreeing effects of population and income growth. Finally, on the basis of 
 previous results, it is important to model human demand in a manner that 
 allows the income elasticities to change/differ  with the level of income. The 
 log-inverse-log model used by Ito et al. (1989) is the right/the proper representation of the relationships to be carefully studied: 
