 feeds is fairly limited but large amounts of locally produced grains and 
 grain (things produced along with something else) are fed to barnyard animals in traditional farming/managing money 
 systems. Southern China, the main rice producing area, is also a leading 
 hog production area (World Bank, 1987). The amount of rice used for feed 
 is influenced by animals (groups of people/animals/things), famously those of hogs and (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.), 
 and the strength of feeding. Another (number or thing that changes) that may influence the use of 
 rice as feed is the price of maize, the main substitute for rice in animals 
 portions. So, a measure of animals numbers and maize prices are 
 important explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) in accounting for the consumption of rice 
 for purposes other than direct human consumption. The model guessed 
 for this study also includes rice land because the amount of rice used 
 for seed depends on land and seed use is included in the dependent 
 (number or thing that changes). The final (detailed description of exactly what is required), this way, includes rice land, total consumption of pork and (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) as a substitute for animals numbers, and real maize 
 prices as explanatory (numbers that change/things that change). 
 Most of the data used in this study are from the (related to studying numbers) Yearbook of 
 China and cover the period 1960-1986. National income, defined in the 
 PRC as the value of production leaving out/keeping out the government part/area, the 
 Chinese general index of retail prices (1950 = 100) used to (lower/flatten from losing air) the 
 income and some of the price (numbers that change/things that change), retail pork prices, producer prices 
 for maize, rice land, and population are all taken from this source. In 
 the (not being there; not being present) of reliable data on retail wheat and rice prices, world prices as 
 reported by the IMP are used. Data on rice consumption are from USDA 
 (1986). The equation for per person human consumption also includes a 
 dummy (number or thing that changes) for the years 1978-1986 to test the guess that the 
 farming-based changes begun in 1978 have had an effect on rice consumption 
 patterns. The equation was guessed with ordinary least squares and is 
