 this study, two income pictures/situations were adopted. Both reflect the expectation 
 that income growth rates will (lower in number/get worse). In the first, the current rate of 7% is 
 maintained into the early 1990's, after which it falls to 5.5% from 1992-96 
 and 4.5% from 1997-2000. The low growth picture/situation uses rates of 5.0%, 
 4.0% and 3.5% for the same periods. The two income levels and the 
 connected income elasticities of demand are shown for selected years in 
 Table 3. 
 Population is the other (number or thing that changes) affecting total human consumption. 
 Because the population of China is very large, small differences in growth 
 rates could lead to large differences in the total number of people. The 
 World Bank has projected population in China to the year 2000. Their 
 projections may underestimate population growth in China because people born in the baby boom of the 1960's are now entering the (related to the process of making children) years. Also, programs to control (away from cities) population growth have 
 not been very effective and the new income streams resulting from the 
 changes in farming-based policies make it easier for (away from cities) families to support 
 added/more children (Lan, 1989). For this study, two population growth 
 paths are assumed. The first allows population to grow at 2.0% per year 
 from 1987 to 1992 and at 1.8% from 1993 to 2000. This leads to a higher 
 (described the future) population in the year 2000 than that (described the future) by the World 
 Bank. The second population growth path is based on the idea (you think is true) that 
 population grows at 1.8% per year until 1992 with the once-a-year growth rate 
 falling to 1.5% after that. The two population projections are shown for 
 1990, 1995 and 2000 in Table 3. Both of them point to/show that the Chinese 
 population will go past 1.3 billion by the year 2000. 
 The income and population projections give rise to four possible combinations. Only two of these, low population growth joined with high 
 income growth and high population growth along with poor growth, 
 are reported in Table 4. The other combinations lead to results between 
 the extremes created by these two growth profiles (Lan, 1989). As shown 
 
