 To project the disappearance of rice for other uses, it is necessary to 
 (describe the future) values for the explanatory (numbers that change/things that change). The projections for rice 
 land and pork and (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) consumption are based on time (popular things/general ways things are going) while 
 the real price of corn was held constant at its average value between 1981 
 and 1985. The projected explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) are shown in Table 5 along 
 with projections of rice consumption for other purposes and total rice 
 disappearance. Total rice disappearance includes human consumption and 
 other uses of rice. In the low population growth/high income growth 
 picture/situation, total disappearance increases by 6.2% from an guessed volume 
 of 128.4 MMT in 1990 to 136.4 MMT in the year 2000. In the picture/situation 
 coupling high population growth with poor growth, total disappearance increases from 131.3 to 147.5 MMT, an increase of 12.3%. Again, using 
 the 1986 figure for per-person use (93 kg) would lead to much 
 higher (statements about the future) for total rice consumption, ranging from 155 to 159 MMT. 
 To understand the effects/results/suggestions of these results, it is helpful to think about 
 some independent projections of Chinese rice production. The World 
 Bank, for example, has (described the future) once-a-year increases of 1.8%. If these 
 increases are (understood/made real/achieved) over the coming ten years, total milled production 
 would reach about 155 MMT in the year 2000. On the basis of the results 
 presented in this study, this production guess hints an exportable 
 
