 extra ranging from 7 to 25 MMT. In another study, Noh (1983) (described the future)Â· 
 that milled production would reach 187.6 MMT by the year 2000. The 
 exportable extra would be even larger if this (statement about the future) is (understood/made real/achieved). Note 
 that (statements about the future) based on (compared to other things) constant levels of per-person use would seriously underestimate the potential excess supply. Using the 
 1986 figure for per-person use, the World Bank production projections and the levels of rice disappearance for other uses (described the future) in this 
 study, Chinese rice disappearance would be about equal to availability in 2000. This shows the importance of allowing income elasticities of 
 demand to change/differ  with the level of income. 
 CONCLUSION 
 
 The results set out above are not came/coming from a complete model with 
 endogenous production and government policy. As the (described the future) slowing in 
 the growth of total human rice consumption becomes seen/obvious, producers 
 and the Chinese government can be expected to react in some way to the 
 changes in consumption patterns. Policies designed to increase rice production may need to be changed because of these changes. As people 
 set apart greater proportions of their growing budgets to high quality 
 products such as meat and dairy products, demand for feed grains can be 
 expected to grow. Given the size of the world rice market (see Table 1), 
 plans based on trading growing excess supplies of rice for imported 
 feed grains do not appear promising. Any sustained increase in the level of 
 rice exports by the PRC is likely to depress world rice prices quite 
 (in a big way), worsening the PRC's terms of trade. A more promising 
 plan may be to put into use policies that encourage feed grain production at 
 the expense of further increases in rice production. (using other choices) some of 
 the current rice land could be moved/changed to rice varieties especially 
 good for feeding animals. Reactions of this nature are likely to result in 
 lower production levels than (described the future) by the World Bank and actual 
 exportable (more than what's needed) will probably be much less than the amounts 
 pointed to/showed in the previous section. 
 Other effects/results/suggestions of the changing consumption patterns in the PRC are 
 harder to detail. In a less controlled market, the slower growth in 
 demand would cause rice prices to (lower in number/get worse) relative to the price of other 
 products (that are bought and sold), benefiting poor people and providing the (rewards or reasons for doing something) to 
 re-set apart useful things/valuable supplies from rice production to feed grain and animals 
 production. In the PRC, the effects may be to encourage production of 
 animals products, vegetables and other foods for the small free market 
 started as part of the farming-based reform. Rice grown in the northern 
 parts of the PRC on land more suited to wheat (producing crops/helping something grow) may be replaced 
 
 78 
 
 E.W.F. PETERSON ET AL. 
 
 with that crop. So, the market for wheat, as well as those for feed grains 
 and animals products may be affected by the (described the future) changes. Much will 
 depend on the response of the government to these changes and the types 
 of price policies put into use. 
 Finally, slower growth in the demand for rice in the PRC will have an 
 hit/effect on world markets for rice, feed grains and, maybe, animals 
 products and wheat. The PRC could possibly become the leading rice 
 exporting country if falling consumption leads to increased exports. It could 
 also become an important market for feed grains if land is not moved/changed from 
 rice production to feed grain production. Because per-person use 
 of rice is likely to fall as incomes increase, the future growth in total rice 
 consumption is likely to be lower than what many planners had expected. 
 This (statement about the future) is especially important in a country where markets cannot 
 be expected to guide the portion of useful things/valuable supplies toward production of other 
 crops and animals products for which demand is likely to increase. 
